The increased facial and axillary hair, enlarged penis and testicle, and normal levels of human chorionic gonadotropin and alpha-fetoprotein suggest Leydig cell tumor, which produces testosterone causing virilization. Seminoma, Sertoli cell tumor, and lymphoma do not typically present with these symptoms.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms suggest precocious puberty, and among the options, only Leydig cell tumor secretes testosterone, which can cause precocious puberty in boys. Seminoma, Sertoli cell tumor, and lymphoma are not associated with precocious puberty.

Among the options, only Leydig cell tumor can cause the excess production of androgens, leading to the development of pubic and axillary hair as well as enlargement of the penis and testicles. The other options are not associated with such symptoms.

The symptoms of increased facial and axillary hair, enlarged penis and testicle, and normal HCG and AFP levels suggest Leydig cell tumor, which is a type of testosterone-secreting tumor. Seminoma and Sertoli cell tumor can cause changes in testicular size and function, but unlikely to cause excessive hair growth. Lymphoma does not typically present with these symptoms.

The increased facial and axillary hair, along with enlarged penis and left testicle, are signs of precocious puberty, and among the options, only Leydig cell tumor can cause this. The normal levels of human chorionic gonadotropin and alpha-fetoprotein rule out Seminoma and Sertoli cell tumor. Lymphoma is unrelated to these symptoms.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The clinical presentation implies testicular enlargement which is usually seen in Leydig cell tumors. The absence of an elevation in human chorionic gonadotropin and alpha-fetoprotein further supports the diagnosis of a Leydig cell tumor, which is typically benign. Seminomas have an elevated alpha-fetoprotein and Sertoli cell tumors typically occur in prepubertal boys. Lymphoma is uncommon in the testes.

The symptoms suggest precocious puberty, and among the options, only Leydig cell tumor can produce testosterone and cause enlargement of the penis and testicle as well as increased body hair. The normal levels of human chorionic gonadotropin and alpha-fetoprotein suggest that the tumor is not malignant.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms suggest precocious puberty, and among the options, Leydig cell tumor is the most likely cause. It is associated with increased testosterone production which leads to the development of secondary sexual characteristics. The enlarged penis and testicle also support this diagnosis. The other options are not associated with increased androgen production.

The symptoms suggest precocious puberty, and among the options, only Leydig cell tumor can cause precocious puberty and increased androgen production leading to hair growth and genital enlargement. Alpha-fetoprotein is not elevated as in a seminoma, and there is no evidence of a testicular tumor or lymphoma.

We refer to the Mayo Clinic website on Leydig cell tumors for help. The increased facial and axillary hair and the enlarged penis and testis suggest that the most likely cause is a Leydig cell tumor, which produces androgens. The other options are not associated with increased androgen production.
